{
  "doc_id": "51117",
  "text": "It has been recognised that battery replacement can be a substantial on-going cost, and contributes significantly to the overall system lifetime cost [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Battery life is reduced when the batteries are deeply discharged when there is prolonged operation at low states of charge or when they are overcharged [CITATION_3] . Studies consider the battery lifetime to be between 3 and 5 years [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] , although lifetimes up to 9 years for lead acid batteries have been reported [CITATION_7] . A number of connected socio-technical factors cause deep battery discharge including growth in demand leading to overloading, poor system design, low-cycle life of existing battery technology, poor component selection, vandalism and theft, and poor system understanding [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] . Although widely treated separately, few studies take an interdisciplinary approach to how social and technical factors affect battery life. In view of the significant effect on the battery system attributed to the decisions of both operators and users, Ulsrud et al. highlight the importance of a socio-technical approach to assessing this type of system [CITATION_13] . Socio-technical approaches are recognised as important in several research areas, particularly for energy systems where both the actions of people and limitations of technology are important factors [CITATION_14] .",
